 Bolton ride Nolan strike to 3rd spot

Bolton: Bolton captain Kevin Nolans long-range strike sent his side rocketing up to third in the Premiership League with a 1-0 win over Tottenham Hotspur at the Reebok Stadium on Monday. 

Nolans seventh goal of the season came in the 32nd minute and was enough to divide two of top flights top teams. 

The match was watched by England coach Sven-Goran Eriksson, who was in the stands to see the Spurs international contingent ahead of Saturdays friendly with Argentina. 

Eriksson left the stadium with Nolan for England ringing in his ears after his stunning strike gave Bolton their third 1-0 win in a row ? with the 23-year-old also the match-winner against Charlton and Zenit St Petersburg. 

Nolan admitted that luck had been on his side as Spurs striker Jermain Defoe had a goal ruled offside and the visitors twice hit the woodwork in the closing stages. 

The win moves Bolton up to third with 23 points from 12 games, eight points behind leaders Chelsea, who stay on 31 after their shock loss on Sunday to Manchester United, with second-placed Wigan Athletic on 25 with a game in hand. 

Nolans goal was reward for a dominant start by the hosts, but Spurs had the ball in the net on 33 minutes, only to see Defoes finish ruled offside before Young-Pyo Lee missed a chance. 

 (AFP) 




